Scaling the data¶

In [18]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
sc=StandardScaler()
xtrain=sc.fit_transform(xtrain)
xtest=sc.fit_transform(xtest)

Developing model¶

In [21]:
def mymodel(model):
    model.fit(xtrain,ytrain)
    ypred=model.predict(xtest)
    
    train=model.score(xtrain,ytrain)
    test=model.score(xtest,ytest)
    
    print(f"Training accuracy:{train}\nTesting accuracy:{test}")
    print(classification_report(ytest,ypred))
    
    return model

This project aimed to develop a machine learning model to predict the people who claim insurance or not according there some features. The dataset used for this project was obtained from the kaggle, containing information on 1338 peoples with 8 features. The dataset was preprocessed by handling missing values, and standardizing data. Seven classification algorithms, including logistic regression,Kneighbors algorithm, and Support Vector Machine, naive_bayes,decision tree,random forest, XGB Classifier, were trained and evaluated on the preprocessed data. The accuracy and confusion matrix were used as performance metrics to compare the models. The Decision tree model achieved the highest accuracy of 100%, followed by Random Forest (100%), xgboost (97.97%), and KNeighbors claassifier (92.94%). The project demonstrated the potential of machine learning techniques for predicting people claim insurance or not and the importance of preprocessing and selecting appropriate models for achieving optimal performance.
